Dybas, \"A Wolf in Jackal's Clothing\", ''Africa Geographic'' (July 2012)\n* Cheryl Lyn Dybas, \"In the Long Shadow of the Pyramids and Beyond: Glimpse of an African... Wolf?\", ''International Wolf Center'' (Spring 2015)\n* [[Hugo van Lawick]] & [[Jane Goodall]] (1971), ''Innocent Killers'', Houghton Mifflin Company Boston\n\n==External links==\n{{Commons category|Canis anthus|African golden wolf (Canis anthus)}}\n{{Wikispecies|Canis anthus|African golden wolf (Canis anthus)}}\n*{{in lang|ar}} [https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=WGUkwFzDZOg Le fant\u00f4me du moyen Atlas \u0634\u0628\u062d \u0627\u0644\u0623\u0637\u0644\u0633 \u0627\u0644\u0645\u062a\u0648\u0633\u0637], ''AmouddouTV'' (Feb 13, 2014)\n*{{in lang|ar}} [https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=qdlUCTnxoW8 Nouveau!! Nouvelle esp\u00e8ce d\u00e9couverte... \u0627\u0643\u062a\u0634\u0627\u0641 \u0646\u0648\u0639 \u062c\u062f\u064a\u062f \u0645\u0646 \u0627\u0644\u062d\u064a\u0648\u0627\u0646\u0627\u062a/ \u062d\u0635\u0631\u064a], ''AmouddouTV'' (Aug 15, 2015)\n{{Carnivora|Ca.}}\n\n{{Taxonbar|from=Q20744349}}\n{{Authority control}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:wolf, golden, African}}\n[[Category:Canis|African golden wolf]]\n[[Category:Canis anthus| ]]\n[[Category:Jackals]]\n[[Category:Wolves|African golden wolf]]\n[[Category:Carnivorans of Africa]]\n[[Category:Mammals of Africa]]\n[[Category:Pleistocene carnivorans]]\n[[Category:Extant Calabrian first appearances]]\n[[Category:Mammals described in 1820|African golden wolf]]\n", "name_user": "Cane-n-able", "label": "safe", "comment": "inaccurate", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/African_golden_wolf"}
{"title_page": "2020 coronavirus pandemic in Ghana", "text_new": "{{short description|Details of ongoing viral pandemic in Ghana}}\n{{Current disaster|event=pandemic|date=January 2020}}\n{{Use dmy dates|date=March 2020}}\n{{EngvarB|date=March 2020}}\n{{Infobox pandemic\n| name            = 2020 coronavirus pandemic in Ghana\n| map1            = \n| legend1         = \n| map2            = \n| legend2         =    \n| map3            = \n| legend3         = \n| disease         = [[COVID-19]]\n| virus_strain    = [[SARS-CoV-2]]\n| location        = [[Ghana]] \n| first_case      = [[Accra]]\n| arrival_date    = 12 March 2020<br />({{Age in years, months, weeks and days|month1=3|day1=12|year1=2020|month2=|day2=|year2=}})\n| origin          = [[Norway]]/[[Turkey]]/[[France]]\n| recovery_cases  = 31\n| deaths          = 5\n| confirmed_cases = 204<ref name=\"mohweb\">{{Cite web |url=https://www.ghanahealthservice.org/covid19/ |title=COVID-19 Updates - Ghana |website=www.ghanahealthservice.org |access-date=1 April 2020}}</ref>\n| suspected_cases = \n| total_ili       = \n| website         = {{URL|https://www.ghanahealthservice.org/covid19}}\n}}\n\nThe '''2020 coronavirus pandemic in Ghana''' is an ongoing [[Viral disease|viral]] [[pandemic]] of [[coronavirus disease 2019]] (COVID-19), a novel infectious disease caused by [[severe acute respiratory syndrome coronavirus 2]] (SARS-CoV-2). The first two cases of COVID-19 in [[Ghana]] during the [[2019\u201320 coronavirus pandemic|2019\u201320 worldwide pandemic]] was confirmed on 12 March 2020, when two people returned from Norway and Turkey.\n__TOC__\n\n== Timeline ==\n{{2019\u201320 coronavirus pandemic data/Ghana medical cases chart}}\n\n* On 11 March, [[President of Ghana|President]] [[Nana Akufo-Addo]] directed the Minister of Finance, [[Ken Ofori-Atta]], to make the [[Ghanaian cedi|cedi]] equivalent of $100 million<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.ghanaweb.com/GhanaHomePage/NewsArchive/Panic-hits-social-media-as-Ghana-confirms-first-cases-of-coronavirus-893413|title=Panic 'hits' social media as Ghana confirms first cases of coronavirus|website=www.ghanaweb.com}}</ref> available to enhance Ghana's coronavirus preparedness and response plan.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.ghanaweb.com/GhanaHomePage/NewsArchive/Coronavirus-MPs-to-have-temperature-tested-before-entering-chamber-Speaker-892792|title=Coronavirus: MPs to have temperature tested before entering chamber - Speaker|website=[[GhanaWeb]]|date=12 March 2020}}</ref>\n* On 12 March 2020 the Health Minister [[Kwaku Agyemang-Manu]] announced Ghana's first '''two cases''' at an emergency press briefing.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://citinewsroom.com/2020/03/two-cases-of-coronavirus-confirmed-in-ghana/|title=Two cases of coronavirus confirmed in Ghana|last=Duncan|first=Jude|date=12 March 2020|website=Citi Newsroom|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=16 March 2020}}</ref> The tests were performed at the [[Noguchi Memorial Institute of Medical Research]], University of Ghana. The two cases were people who came back to the country from Norway and Turkey, beginning the [[contact tracing]] process.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.bbc.com/pidgin/tori-51867414|title=Ghana don record first Coronavirus cases - Read wetin we know so far|date=13 March 2020|website=[[BBC News]]|version=(in Pidgin English)}}</ref> One case is a senior officer at the Norwegian Embassy in Ghana who had returned from Norway,<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://citinewsroom.com/2020/03/coronavirus-norwegian-embassy-in-ghana-shuts-down-after-staff-member-tested-positive/|title=Coronavirus: Norwegian Embassy in Ghana shuts down after staff member tested positive|last=Anyorigya|first=Daniel|date=13 March 2020|website=Citi Newsroom|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=16 March 2020}}</ref> while the other was a staff member at the UN offices in Ghana who had returned from Turkey.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.graphic.com.gh/news/general-news/un-shuts-down-office-in-ghana-following-one-staff-testing-positive-for-coronavirus.html|title=UN Ghana staff tests positive for Coronavirus, office shutdown|website=Graphic Online|language=en|access-date=18 March 2020}}</ref>\n* On 13 March 2020 Ghana confirmed '''two cases''' which summed up to '''four cases''' in the country.\n*On 14 March 2020 Ghana confirmed '''two cases''' which summed up to '''six cases''' in the country.\n*On 15 March 2020, four new cases were confirmed in a live telecast by the Ministry of Health and Minister of Information. Traveling to Ghana had been strongly discouraged until further notice and non-admittance of travellers from countries where at least 200 cases of COVID-19 were recorded was declared; this restriction did not apply to Ghanaian citizens and people with resident permits.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.ghanabusinessnews.com/2020/03/15/ghana-covid-19-cases-rise-to-six/|title=Ghana COVID-19 cases rise to six|date=15 March 2020|website=Ghana Business News|language=English}}</ref><ref>{{Cite news|last=Duncan|first=Jude|url=https://citinewsroom.com/2020/03/coronavirus-travellers-from-countries-with-over-200-cases-wont-be-allowed-in-ghana/|title=Coronavirus: Travellers from countries with over 200 cases won't be allowed in Ghana|date=15 March 2020|work=Citi Newsroom|access-date=|url-status=live}}</ref> A web page<ref name=\"mohweb\" /> was also created to provide official updates and information.\n*On 15 March 2020 at 10 pm, [[President of Ghana|President]] [[Nana Akufo-Addo]] banned all public gatherings including conferences, workshops, funerals, festivals, political rallies, church activities and other related events to reduce the spread of COVID-19 at a press briefing on the state of COVID-19. Basic schools, senior high schools and universities, both public and private, have also been closed. Only [[BECE]] and [[WASSCE]] candidates are permitted to remain in school under social distancing protocols.<ref>{{Cite news|last=Nyabor|first=Jonas|url=https://citinewsroom.com/2020/03/government-bans-church-activities-funerals-all-other-public-gatherings/|title=Coronavirus: Government bans religious activities, funerals, all other public gatherings|date=15 March 2020|work=Citi Newsroom|access-date=16 March 2020|url-status=live}}</ref>\n*On 17 March 2020, the Minister of Finance, [[Ken Ofori-Atta]], declared in Parliament that the $100 million announced by President Akufo-Addo to fight coronavirus is not ready<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://starrfm.com.gh/2020/03/covid-19-akufo-ghana-goes-to-imf-wb-for-akufo-addos-100m/|title=Covid-19: Ghana goes to IMF, WB for Akufo-Addo\u2019s $100m {{!}} Starr Fm|last=Starrfmonline|language=en-US|access-date=2020-04-01}}</ref>. This revelation by the Minister did not go down well with many Ghanaians slamming the president for not being sincere and honest in such a precarious situation<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.ghanaweb.com/GhanaHomePage/NewsArchive/Are-you-a-magician-to-spend-money-you-don-t-have-Akufo-Addo-blasted-over-100m-coronavirus-money-897598|title=Are you a magician to spend money you don\u2019t have? \u2013 Akufo-Addo blasted over $100m coronavirus money|website=www.ghanaweb.com|language=en|access-date=2020-04-01}}</ref>. Also on this day, Ghana confirmed '''another case''' which sums up to '''seven cases''' recorded in the Greater Accra Region.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://citinewsroom.com/2020/03/one-more-coronavirus-case-confirmed-in-ghana/|title=One more Coronavirus case confirmed in Ghana|date=17 March 2020|website=Citi Newsroom|language=en-US|access-date=17 March 2020}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.graphic.com.gh/news/general-news/ghana-records-7th-confirmed-coronavirus-case.html|title=Ghana records 7th confirmed Coronavirus case|website=Graphic Online|language=en|access-date=17 March 2020}}</ref>\n*On 18 March 2020, Ghana records '''two cases''' which sums up to '''nine cases .''' These were confirmed by NMIMR, both Ghanaians returning from the [[United Kingdom]] and the [[United Arab Emirates]]. On the same day, three Ghanaians in [[Europe]] died from the disease.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.graphic.com.gh/news/general-news/coronavirus-kills-3-ghanaians-ayorkor-botchwey.html|title=Coronavirus kills 3 Ghanaians - Ayorkor Botchwey|website=Graphic Online|language=en|access-date=19 March 2020}}</ref>\n*On 19 March 2020, KCCR confirmed '''two new cases''' in [[Kumasi]], [[Ashanti Region]], bringing the number of confirmed cases in the country to '''11'''.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.graphic.com.gh/news/general-news/ghana-s-coronavirus-confirmed-cases-increases-to-11.html|title=Ghana: Coronavirus cases increases to 11|website=Graphic Online|language=en|access-date=19 March 2020}}</ref> Passport services were also suspended on this date.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.graphic.com.gh/news/general-news/ghana-news-coronavirus-foreign-ministry-suspends-all-passport-services.html|title=Coronavirus: Foreign Ministry suspends all passport services|website=Graphic Online|language=en|access-date=19 March 2020}}</ref>\n*On 20 March 2020, Ghana records '''five new cases''' were confirmed in the Greater Accra Region, raising total confirmed cases to 16.{{citation needed|date=March 2020}}<ref>{{Cite news|last=Arhinful|first=Ernest|url=https://citinewsroom.com/2020/03/coronavirus-cases-in-ghana-rise-to-16/|title=Coronavirus cases in Ghana rise to 16|date=20 March 2020|work=Citi Newsroom|access-date=28 March 2020|url-status=live}}</ref>\n*On 21 March 2020, Ghana confirms '''three new cases''' which sums up to 19 patients. At 9 pm, [[Nana Akuffo Addo]] addressed the nation with Ghana's '''first death case''' from [[Kumasi]].<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.ghanaweb.com/GhanaHomePage/NewsArchive/Identity-of-Ghana-s-first-coronavirus-dead-victim-revealed-900883|title=Identity of Ghana's first coronavirus dead victim revealed|website=www.ghanaweb.com|language=en|access-date=2020-03-23}}</ref> '''Two new cases''' were later confirmed making total of '''twenty-one confirmed''' in Ghana.<ref name=\"mohweb\"/>\n*On 22 March 2020, '''three cases''' were confirmed in the country hence summing up to '''24 cases'''.<ref>{{Cite news|last=Adogla-Bessa|first=Delali|url=https://citinewsroom.com/2020/03/coronavirus-cases-in-ghana-rise-to-24/|title=Coronavirus cases in Ghana rise to 24|date=22 March 2020|work=Citi Newsroom|access-date=28 March 2020|url-status=live}}</ref>\n*On 23 March 2020, three cases were recorded which summed up to '''27 cases'''. The Local Government Minister announced the disinfection of 137 markets in the Greater Accra Region.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.graphic.com.gh/news/general-news/markets-in-accra-tema-being-disinfected-to-prevent-coronavirus-spread.html|title=Markets in Accra, Tema being disinfected to prevent Coronavirus spread (VIDEO)|website=Graphic Online|language=en|access-date=2020-03-23}}</ref><ref>{{Cite news|last=Adogla-Bessa|first=Delali|url=https://citinewsroom.com/2020/03/137-markets-to-be-affected-by-mondays-disinfection-exercise-local-government-ministry/|title=137 markets to be affected by Monday's disinfection exercise \u2013 Local Government Ministry|date=22 March 2020|work=Citi Newsroom|access-date=28 March 2020|url-status=live}}</ref> On that same day, all beaches were closed to help contain the spread of the pandemic.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.graphic.com.gh/news/general-news/ghana-news-coronavirus-gta-closes-all-beaches-in-ghana.html|title=All beaches in Ghana closed to fight Coronavirus|website=Graphic Online|language=en|access-date=2020-03-23}}</ref> All of the county's borders were closed for a fortnight from midnight of Sunday the 22nd of March 2020.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.graphic.com.gh/news/general-news/ghana-news-coronavirus-borders-closed-directive-will-last-2-weeks.html|title=Ghana closes its borders for 2 weeks to fight Coronavirus|website=Graphic Online|language=en|access-date=2020-03-23}}</ref>\n*On 24 March 2020 the Minister of Health announced '''25 new confirmed cases''' and one new death case, hence totaling '''52 COVID-19 patients''' and two deaths.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://citinewsroom.com/2020/03/coronavirus-cases-in-ghana-jump-to-52/|title=Coronavirus cases in Ghana jump to 52|date=2020-03-24|website=Citinewsroom - Comprehensive News in Ghana, Current Affairs, Business News , Headlines, Ghana Sports, Entertainment, Politics|language=en-US|access-date=2020-03-24}}</ref>\n*On 25 March 2020,  there were '''15 cases''' with a '''third death''' was recorded at the [[37 Military Hospital|37 military hospital]] and an update from the [[Ghana Health Service]] brought the number of '''cases to 68'''.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.myjoyonline.com/news/health/ghana-records-third-coronavirus-death-at-37-military-hospital/|title=Ghana records third coronavirus death at 37 Military Hospital|date=2020-03-25|website=MyJoyOnline.com|language=en-US|access-date=2020-03-25}}</ref><ref>{{Cite news|last=Adogla-Bessa|first=Delali|url=https://citinewsroom.com/2020/03/update-coronavirus-cases-in-ghana-hit-68/|title=Update: Coronavirus cases in Ghana hit 68|date=25 March 2020|work=Citi Newsroom|access-date=28 March 2020|url-status=live}}</ref>\n*On 26 March 2020, '''64 new cases''' were recorded which leads to a sum of '''132 cases''' in Ghana.<ref>{{Cite news|last=Nyabor|first=Jonas|url=https://citinewsroom.com/2020/03/ghanas-coronavirus-case-count-rises-to-132/|title=Ghana's Coronavirus case count rises to 132|date=26 March 2020|work=Citi Newsroom|access-date=28 March 2020|url-status=live}}</ref> On the same day, a letter written and signed by the Director General of the Ghana Health Service recalled all staff on study leave into active service. This was to help accommodate the workload on health centres.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.graphic.com.gh/news/general-news/all-ghana-health-service-staff-on-study-leave-recalled-for-coronavirus-fight.html|title=All Ghana Health Service staff on study leave recalled for Coronavirus 'fight'|website=Graphic Online|language=en|access-date=2020-03-28}}</ref>\n*On 27 March 2020, Ghana confirmed '''three cases''' with a total of '''137 cases'''.<ref>{{Cite news|last=Nyabor|first=Jonas|url=https://citinewsroom.com/2020/03/covid-19-four-new-cases-raise-ghanas-count-to-136/|title=COVID-19: Four new cases raise Ghana's count to 136|date=27 March 2020|work=Citi Newsroom|access-date=28 March 2020|url-status=live}}</ref> The first case recorded in the '''Upper West Region''' was made known at press briefing in '''Wa'''.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.graphic.com.gh/news/general-news/wa-records-coronavirus-case-upper-west-regional-minister-confirms.html|title=Wa records Coronavirus case - Upper West Regional Minister confirms|website=Graphic Online|language=en|access-date=2020-03-28}}</ref> The '''President''' addressed the nation at 11pm<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.graphic.com.gh/news/general-news/president-akufo-addo-addresses-nation-at-11pm.html|title=President Akufo-Addo addresses Nation at 11pm|website=Graphic Online|language=en|access-date=2020-03-28}}</ref> with an announcement, that placed some key cities in '''Accra''' and '''Kumasi''' under a partial lock down, effective from '''Monday 30 March 2020'''.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.graphic.com.gh/news/politics/accra-tema-kasoa-and-kumasi-under-partial-lockdown.html|title=Accra, Tema, Kasoa and Kumasi under partial lockdown|website=Graphic Online|language=en|access-date=2020-03-28}}</ref> Some services such as Members of the Executive, Legislature and the Judiciary; Production, distribution and marketing of food, beverages, pharmaceuticals, medicine, paper and plastic packages were exempted from the restrictions.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://focusnewsroom.com/2020/03/28/akufo-addo-announces-partial-lockdown-of-accra-kumasi-tema-to-curb-covid-19-spread/|title=Akufo-Addo announces partial lockdown of Accra, Kumasi, Tema to curb COVID-19 spread|date=2020-03-28|website=Focus Fm|language=en-US|access-date=2020-03-28}}</ref>\n*On 28 March 2020 the total number of confirmed cases rose to '''141''' and the total number of deaths stood at '''five'''.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.graphic.com.gh/news/general-news/coronavirus-ghana-records-141-confirmed-cases.html|title=Coronavirus: Ghana records 141 confirmed cases|website=Graphic Online|language=en|access-date=2020-03-29}}</ref> A special life insurance cover for the professionals at the frontline dealing with the pandemic,was announced by the '''Ghana Health Ministry'''. The workers were insured under '''Group Life cover''',with an assured sum of '''GHS 350,000''' on each life.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.graphic.com.gh/news/general-news/coronavirus-ghana-announces-special-life-insurance-cover-for-health-workers.html|title=Coronavirus: Ghana announces special life insurance cover for health workers|website=Graphic Online|language=en|access-date=2020-04-02}}</ref>\n*On 29 March 2020 the government of Ghana set up a quarantine centre at the Northern Regional capital, Tamale after the confirmation of 10 new cases of COVID-19 recorded in that part of the country bringing the number of case count for COVID-19 to '''152.'''<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://citinewsroom.com/2020/03/coronavirus-quarantine-centre-set-up-in-tamale-drones-to-transport-blood-samples-health-minister/|title=Coronavirus: Quarantine centre set up in Tamale, drones to transport blood samples \u2013 Health Minister|date=2020-03-29|website=Citinewsroom - Comprehensive News in Ghana, Current Affairs,  Business News , Headlines, Ghana Sports, Entertainment, Politics,|language=en-US|access-date=2020-03-29}}</ref>\n*On 30 March 2020 the partial lock down of Accra and Kumasi took effect<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://starrfm.com.gh/2020/03/covid-19-accra-kumasi-empty-as-lockdown-takes-effect/|title=Covid-19: Accra, Kumasi empty as lockdown takes effect {{!}} Starr Fm|last=Acheampong|first=Kwame|language=en-US|access-date=2020-04-02}}</ref> No new cases were recorded on this day.<ref name=\":0\">{{Cite web|url=https://ghanahealthservice.org/covid19/|title=COVID-19 Updates {{!}} Ghana|website=ghanahealthservice.org|access-date=2020-04-02}}</ref>\n; affected districts in the Greater Accra Region:\n* Accra Metropolis\n* Tema Metropolis\n* Tema West\n* Kpone Katamanso\n* Krowor\n* Ledzokuku\n* Adentan\n* Ashiaman\n* La-Nkwantanang-Madina\n* La-Dade-Kotopon\n* Okaikwei North\n* Ablekuma North\n* Ablekuma West\n* Ablekuma Central\n* Ayawaso East\n* Ayawaso North\n* Ayawaso West\n* Ayawaso Central\n* Ga North\n* Ga West\n* Ga South\n* Ga Central\n* Ga East\n* Korle-Klottey\n* Awutu Senya East\n\n; affected districts in Ashanti Region:\n* Kumasi Metropolis\n* Asokwa\n* Suame\n* Old Tafo\n* Oforikrom\n* Asokore Mampong\n* Kwadaso\n* Atwima Nwabiagya\n* Kwabre East\n* Ejisu,Afigya-Kwabre South\n* Bosomtwe\n* Atwima Kwanwoma\n* Atwima Nwabiagya North\n*On '''31<sup>st</sup> March 2020''','''nine''' new cases were confirmed bringing the number to '''161'''. The new cases were all in Accra. Three of the infected persons had returned from journeys to Germany, France and Hungary. <ref name=\":0\" />\n*On 1 April 2020, the number of confirmed cases reached '''195''' with more security checkpoints and roadblocks set up in Accra. There was a bit of heavy vehicular traffic at many of the barriers and most commercial vehicles were not allowed to cross the Tema motorway.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.graphic.com.gh/news/general-news/lockdown-day-3-stranded-passengers-canes-traffic-no-mercy-for-trotros.html|title=#Lockdown Day 3: Stranded passengers, canes, traffic, no mercy for trotros|website=Graphic Online|language=en|access-date=2020-04-02}}</ref>\n*On 2 April 2020,'''nine''' new cases are confirmed, making the total '''204'''. All new cases are from the Greater Accra Region. The '''nine''' cases consist of '''four''' who have no contact with confirmed cases nor a travel history,'''four''' who are contacts of confirmed cases and one traveling to Ghana from Benin within the last '''14''' days.<ref name=\":0\" /> '''Two''' cases are in critical condition.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.graphic.com.gh/news/general-news/coronavirus-ghana-s-cases-hit-204-two-in-critical-condition.html|title=Coronavirus: Ghana's cases hit 204, two in critical condition|website=Graphic Online|language=en|access-date=2020-04-02}}</ref>\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist}}\n\n{{COVID-19}}\n\n[[Category:2019\u201320 coronavirus pandemic by country and territory|Ghana]]\n[[Category:2020 coronavirus pandemic in Africa|Ghana]]\n[[Category:2020 in Ghana|coronavirus pandemic]]\n[[Category:Medical outbreaks in Ghana]]\n", "text_old": "{{short description|Details of ongoing viral pandemic in Ghana}}\n{{Current disaster|event=pandemic|date=January 2020}}\n{{Use dmy dates|date=March 2020}}\n{{EngvarB|date=March 2020}}\n{{Infobox pandemic\n| name            = 2020 coronavirus pandemic in Ghana\n| map1            = \n| legend1         = \n| map2            = \n| legend2         =    \n| map3            = \n| legend3         = \n| disease         = [[COVID-19]]\n| virus_strain    = [[SARS-CoV-2]]\n| location        = [[Ghana]] \n| first_case      = [[Accra]]\n| arrival_date    = 12 March 2020<br />({{Age in years, months, weeks and days|month1=3|day1=12|year1=2020|month2=|day2=|year2=}})\n| origin          = [[Norway]]/[[Turkey]]/[[France]]\n| recovery_cases  = 31\n| deaths          = 5\n| confirmed_cases = 204<ref name=\"mohweb\">{{Cite web |url=https://www.ghanahealthservice.org/covid19/ |title=COVID-19 Updates - Ghana |website=www.ghanahealthservice.org |access-date=1 April 2020}}</ref>\n| suspected_cases = \n| total_ili       = \n| website         = {{URL|https://www.ghanahealthservice.org/covid19}}\n}}\n\nThe '''2020 coronavirus pandemic in Ghana''' is an ongoing [[Viral disease|viral]] [[pandemic]] of [[coronavirus disease 2019]] (COVID-19), a novel infectious disease caused by [[severe acute respiratory syndrome coronavirus 2]] (SARS-CoV-2). The first two cases of COVID-19 in [[Ghana]] during the [[2019\u201320 coronavirus pandemic|2019\u201320 worldwide pandemic]] was confirmed on 12 March 2020, when two people returned from Norway and Turkey.\n__TOC__\n\n== Timeline ==\n{{2019\u201320 coronavirus pandemic data/Ghana medical cases chart}}\n\n* On 11 March, [[President of Ghana|President]] [[Nana Akufo-Addo]] directed the Minister of Finance, [[Ken Ofori-Atta]], to make the [[Ghanaian cedi|cedi]] equivalent of $100 million<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.ghanaweb.com/GhanaHomePage/NewsArchive/Panic-hits-social-media-as-Ghana-confirms-first-cases-of-coronavirus-893413|title=Panic 'hits' social media as Ghana confirms first cases of coronavirus|website=www.ghanaweb.com}}</ref> available to enhance Ghana's coronavirus preparedness and response plan.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.ghanaweb.com/GhanaHomePage/NewsArchive/Coronavirus-MPs-to-have-temperature-tested-before-entering-chamber-Speaker-892792|title=Coronavirus: MPs to have temperature tested before entering chamber - Speaker|website=[[GhanaWeb]]|date=12 March 2020}}</ref>\n* On 12 March 2020 the Health Minister [[Kwaku Agyemang-Manu]] announced Ghana's first '''two cases''' at an emergency press briefing.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://citinewsroom.com/2020/03/two-cases-of-coronavirus-confirmed-in-ghana/|title=Two cases of coronavirus confirmed in Ghana|last=Duncan|first=Jude|date=12 March 2020|website=Citi Newsroom|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=16 March 2020}}</ref> The tests were performed at the [[Noguchi Memorial Institute of Medical Research]], University of Ghana. The two cases were people who came back to the country from Norway and Turkey, beginning the [[contact tracing]] process.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.bbc.com/pidgin/tori-51867414|title=Ghana don record first Coronavirus cases - Read wetin we know so far|date=13 March 2020|website=[[BBC News]]|version=(in Pidgin English)}}</ref> One case is a senior officer at the Norwegian Embassy in Ghana who had returned from Norway,<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://citinewsroom.com/2020/03/coronavirus-norwegian-embassy-in-ghana-shuts-down-after-staff-member-tested-positive/|title=Coronavirus: Norwegian Embassy in Ghana shuts down after staff member tested positive|last=Anyorigya|first=Daniel|date=13 March 2020|website=Citi Newsroom|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=16 March 2020}}</ref> while the other was a staff member at the UN offices in Ghana who had returned from Turkey.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.graphic.com.gh/news/general-news/un-shuts-down-office-in-ghana-following-one-staff-testing-positive-for-coronavirus.html|title=UN Ghana staff tests positive for Coronavirus, office shutdown|website=Graphic Online|language=en|access-date=18 March 2020}}</ref>\n* On 13 March 2020 Ghana confirmed '''two cases''' which summed up to '''four cases''' in the country.\n*On 14 March 2020 Ghana confirmed '''two cases''' which summed up to '''six cases''' in the country.\n*On 15 March 2020, four new cases were confirmed in a live telecast by the Ministry of Health and Minister of Information. Traveling to Ghana has been strongly discouraged until further notice and non-admittance of travellers from countries where at least 200 cases of COVID-19 were recorded was declared; this restriction does not apply to Ghanaian citizens and people with resident permits.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.ghanabusinessnews.com/2020/03/15/ghana-covid-19-cases-rise-to-six/|title=Ghana COVID-19 cases rise to six|date=15 March 2020|website=Ghana Business News|language=English}}</ref><ref>{{Cite news|last=Duncan|first=Jude|url=https://citinewsroom.com/2020/03/coronavirus-travellers-from-countries-with-over-200-cases-wont-be-allowed-in-ghana/|title=Coronavirus: Travellers from countries with over 200 cases won't be allowed in Ghana|date=15 March 2020|work=Citi Newsroom|access-date=|url-status=live}}</ref> A web page<ref name=\"mohweb\" /> was also created to provide official updates and information.\n*On 15 March 2020 at 10 pm, [[President of Ghana|President]] [[Nana Akufo-Addo]] banned all public gatherings including conferences, workshops, funerals, festivals, political rallies, church activities and other related events to reduce the spread of COVID-19 at a press briefing on the state of COVID-19. Basic schools, senior high schools and universities, both public and private, have also been closed. Only [[BECE]] and [[WASSCE]] candidates are permitted to remain in school under social distancing protocols.<ref>{{Cite news|last=Nyabor|first=Jonas|url=https://citinewsroom.com/2020/03/government-bans-church-activities-funerals-all-other-public-gatherings/|title=Coronavirus: Government bans religious activities, funerals, all other public gatherings|date=15 March 2020|work=Citi Newsroom|access-date=16 March 2020|url-status=live}}</ref>\n*On 17 March 2020, the Minister of Finance, [[Ken Ofori-Atta]], declared in Parliament that the $100 million announced by President Akufo-Addo to fight coronavirus is not ready<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://starrfm.com.gh/2020/03/covid-19-akufo-ghana-goes-to-imf-wb-for-akufo-addos-100m/|title=Covid-19: Ghana goes to IMF, WB for Akufo-Addo\u2019s $100m {{!}} Starr Fm|last=Starrfmonline|language=en-US|access-date=2020-04-01}}</ref>. This revelation by the Minister did not go down well with many Ghanaians slamming the president for not being sincere and honest in such a precarious situation<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.ghanaweb.com/GhanaHomePage/NewsArchive/Are-you-a-magician-to-spend-money-you-don-t-have-Akufo-Addo-blasted-over-100m-coronavirus-money-897598|title=Are you a magician to spend money you don\u2019t have? \u2013 Akufo-Addo blasted over $100m coronavirus money|website=www.ghanaweb.com|language=en|access-date=2020-04-01}}</ref>. Also on this day, Ghana confirmed '''another case''' which sums up to '''seven cases''' recorded in the Greater Accra Region.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://citinewsroom.com/2020/03/one-more-coronavirus-case-confirmed-in-ghana/|title=One more Coronavirus case confirmed in Ghana|date=17 March 2020|website=Citi Newsroom|language=en-US|access-date=17 March 2020}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.graphic.com.gh/news/general-news/ghana-records-7th-confirmed-coronavirus-case.html|title=Ghana records 7th confirmed Coronavirus case|website=Graphic Online|language=en|access-date=17 March 2020}}</ref>\n*On 18 March 2020, Ghana records '''two cases''' which sums up to '''nine cases .''' These were confirmed by NMIMR, both Ghanaians returning from the [[United Kingdom]] and the [[United Arab Emirates]]. On the same day, three Ghanaians in [[Europe]] died from the disease.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.graphic.com.gh/news/general-news/coronavirus-kills-3-ghanaians-ayorkor-botchwey.html|title=Coronavirus kills 3 Ghanaians - Ayorkor Botchwey|website=Graphic Online|language=en|access-date=19 March 2020}}</ref>\n*On 19 March 2020, KCCR confirmed '''two new cases''' in [[Kumasi]], [[Ashanti Region]], bringing the number of confirmed cases in the country to '''11'''.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.graphic.com.gh/news/general-news/ghana-s-coronavirus-confirmed-cases-increases-to-11.html|title=Ghana: Coronavirus cases increases to 11|website=Graphic Online|language=en|access-date=19 March 2020}}</ref> Passport services were also suspended on this date.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.graphic.com.gh/news/general-news/ghana-news-coronavirus-foreign-ministry-suspends-all-passport-services.html|title=Coronavirus: Foreign Ministry suspends all passport services|website=Graphic Online|language=en|access-date=19 March 2020}}</ref>\n*On 20 March 2020, Ghana records '''five new cases''' were confirmed in the Greater Accra Region, raising total confirmed cases to 16.{{citation needed|date=March 2020}}<ref>{{Cite news|last=Arhinful|first=Ernest|url=https://citinewsroom.com/2020/03/coronavirus-cases-in-ghana-rise-to-16/|title=Coronavirus cases in Ghana rise to 16|date=20 March 2020|work=Citi Newsroom|access-date=28 March 2020|url-status=live}}</ref>\n*On 21 March 2020, Ghana confirms '''three new cases''' which sums up to 19 patients. At 9 pm, [[Nana Akuffo Addo]] addressed the nation with Ghana's '''first death case''' from [[Kumasi]].<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.ghanaweb.com/GhanaHomePage/NewsArchive/Identity-of-Ghana-s-first-coronavirus-dead-victim-revealed-900883|title=Identity of Ghana's first coronavirus dead victim revealed|website=www.ghanaweb.com|language=en|access-date=2020-03-23}}</ref> '''Two new cases''' were later confirmed making total of '''twenty-one confirmed''' in Ghana.<ref name=\"mohweb\"/>\n*On 22 March 2020, '''three cases''' were confirmed in the country hence summing up to '''24 cases'''.<ref>{{Cite news|last=Adogla-Bessa|first=Delali|url=https://citinewsroom.com/2020/03/coronavirus-cases-in-ghana-rise-to-24/|title=Coronavirus cases in Ghana rise to 24|date=22 March 2020|work=Citi Newsroom|access-date=28 March 2020|url-status=live}}</ref>\n*On 23 March 2020, three cases were recorded which summed up to '''27 cases'''. The Local Government Minister announced the disinfection of 137 markets in the Greater Accra Region.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.graphic.com.gh/news/general-news/markets-in-accra-tema-being-disinfected-to-prevent-coronavirus-spread.html|title=Markets in Accra, Tema being disinfected to prevent Coronavirus spread (VIDEO)|website=Graphic Online|language=en|access-date=2020-03-23}}</ref><ref>{{Cite news|last=Adogla-Bessa|first=Delali|url=https://citinewsroom.com/2020/03/137-markets-to-be-affected-by-mondays-disinfection-exercise-local-government-ministry/|title=137 markets to be affected by Monday's disinfection exercise \u2013 Local Government Ministry|date=22 March 2020|work=Citi Newsroom|access-date=28 March 2020|url-status=live}}</ref> On that same day, all beaches were closed to help contain the spread of the pandemic.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.graphic.com.gh/news/general-news/ghana-news-coronavirus-gta-closes-all-beaches-in-ghana.html|title=All beaches in Ghana closed to fight Coronavirus|website=Graphic Online|language=en|access-date=2020-03-23}}</ref> All of the county's borders were closed for a fortnight from midnight of Sunday the 22nd of March 2020.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.graphic.com.gh/news/general-news/ghana-news-coronavirus-borders-closed-directive-will-last-2-weeks.html|title=Ghana closes its borders for 2 weeks to fight Coronavirus|website=Graphic Online|language=en|access-date=2020-03-23}}</ref>\n*On 24 March 2020 the Minister of Health announced '''25 new confirmed cases''' and one new death case, hence totaling '''52 COVID-19 patients''' and two deaths.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://citinewsroom.com/2020/03/coronavirus-cases-in-ghana-jump-to-52/|title=Coronavirus cases in Ghana jump to 52|date=2020-03-24|website=Citinewsroom - Comprehensive News in Ghana, Current Affairs, Business News , Headlines, Ghana Sports, Entertainment, Politics|language=en-US|access-date=2020-03-24}}</ref>\n*On 25 March 2020,  there were '''15 cases''' with a '''third death''' was recorded at the [[37 Military Hospital|37 military hospital]] and an update from the [[Ghana Health Service]] brought the number of '''cases to 68'''.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.myjoyonline.com/news/health/ghana-records-third-coronavirus-death-at-37-military-hospital/|title=Ghana records third coronavirus death at 37 Military Hospital|date=2020-03-25|website=MyJoyOnline.com|language=en-US|access-date=2020-03-25}}</ref><ref>{{Cite news|last=Adogla-Bessa|first=Delali|url=https://citinewsroom.com/2020/03/update-coronavirus-cases-in-ghana-hit-68/|title=Update: Coronavirus cases in Ghana hit 68|date=25 March 2020|work=Citi Newsroom|access-date=28 March 2020|url-status=live}}</ref>\n*On 26 March 2020, '''64 new cases''' were recorded which leads to a sum of '''132 cases''' in Ghana.<ref>{{Cite news|last=Nyabor|first=Jonas|url=https://citinewsroom.com/2020/03/ghanas-coronavirus-case-count-rises-to-132/|title=Ghana's Coronavirus case count rises to 132|date=26 March 2020|work=Citi Newsroom|access-date=28 March 2020|url-status=live}}</ref> On the same day, a letter written and signed by the Director General of the Ghana Health Service recalled all staff on study leave into active service. This was to help accommodate the workload on health centres.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.graphic.com.gh/news/general-news/all-ghana-health-service-staff-on-study-leave-recalled-for-coronavirus-fight.html|title=All Ghana Health Service staff on study leave recalled for Coronavirus 'fight'|website=Graphic Online|language=en|access-date=2020-03-28}}</ref>\n*On 27 March 2020, Ghana confirmed '''three cases''' with a total of '''137 cases'''.<ref>{{Cite news|last=Nyabor|first=Jonas|url=https://citinewsroom.com/2020/03/covid-19-four-new-cases-raise-ghanas-count-to-136/|title=COVID-19: Four new cases raise Ghana's count to 136|date=27 March 2020|work=Citi Newsroom|access-date=28 March 2020|url-status=live}}</ref> The first case recorded in the '''Upper West Region''' was made known at press briefing in '''Wa'''.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.graphic.com.gh/news/general-news/wa-records-coronavirus-case-upper-west-regional-minister-confirms.html|title=Wa records Coronavirus case - Upper West Regional Minister confirms|website=Graphic Online|language=en|access-date=2020-03-28}}</ref> The '''President''' addressed the nation at 11pm<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.graphic.com.gh/news/general-news/president-akufo-addo-addresses-nation-at-11pm.html|title=President Akufo-Addo addresses Nation at 11pm|website=Graphic Online|language=en|access-date=2020-03-28}}</ref> with an announcement, that placed some key cities in '''Accra''' and '''Kumasi''' under a partial lock down, effective from '''Monday 30 March 2020'''.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.graphic.com.gh/news/politics/accra-tema-kasoa-and-kumasi-under-partial-lockdown.html|title=Accra, Tema, Kasoa and Kumasi under partial lockdown|website=Graphic Online|language=en|access-date=2020-03-28}}</ref> Some services such as Members of the Executive, Legislature and the Judiciary; Production, distribution and marketing of food, beverages, pharmaceuticals, medicine, paper and plastic packages were exempted from the restrictions.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://focusnewsroom.com/2020/03/28/akufo-addo-announces-partial-lockdown-of-accra-kumasi-tema-to-curb-covid-19-spread/|title=Akufo-Addo announces partial lockdown of Accra, Kumasi, Tema to curb COVID-19 spread|date=2020-03-28|website=Focus Fm|language=en-US|access-date=2020-03-28}}</ref>\n*On 28 March 2020 the total number of confirmed cases rose to '''141''' and the total number of deaths stood at '''five'''.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.graphic.com.gh/news/general-news/coronavirus-ghana-records-141-confirmed-cases.html|title=Coronavirus: Ghana records 141 confirmed cases|website=Graphic Online|language=en|access-date=2020-03-29}}</ref> A special life insurance cover for the professionals at the frontline dealing with the pandemic,was announced by the '''Ghana Health Ministry'''. The workers were insured under '''Group Life cover''',with an assured sum of '''GHS 350,000''' on each life.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.graphic.com.gh/news/general-news/coronavirus-ghana-announces-special-life-insurance-cover-for-health-workers.html|title=Coronavirus: Ghana announces special life insurance cover for health workers|website=Graphic Online|language=en|access-date=2020-04-02}}</ref>\n*On 29 March 2020 the government of Ghana set up a quarantine centre at the Northern Regional capital, Tamale after the confirmation of 10 new cases of COVID-19 recorded in that part of the country bringing the number of case count for COVID-19 to '''152.'''<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://citinewsroom.com/2020/03/coronavirus-quarantine-centre-set-up-in-tamale-drones-to-transport-blood-samples-health-minister/|title=Coronavirus: Quarantine centre set up in Tamale, drones to transport blood samples \u2013 Health Minister|date=2020-03-29|website=Citinewsroom - Comprehensive News in Ghana, Current Affairs,  Business News , Headlines, Ghana Sports, Entertainment, Politics,|language=en-US|access-date=2020-03-29}}</ref>\n*On 30 March 2020 the partial lock down of Accra and Kumasi took effect<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://starrfm.com.gh/2020/03/covid-19-accra-kumasi-empty-as-lockdown-takes-effect/|title=Covid-19: Accra, Kumasi empty as lockdown takes effect {{!}} Starr Fm|last=Acheampong|first=Kwame|language=en-US|access-date=2020-04-02}}</ref> No new cases were recorded on this day.<ref name=\":0\">{{Cite web|url=https://ghanahealthservice.org/covid19/|title=COVID-19 Updates {{!}} Ghana|website=ghanahealthservice.org|access-date=2020-04-02}}</ref>\n; affected districts in the Greater Accra Region:\n* Accra Metropolis\n* Tema Metropolis\n* Tema West\n* Kpone Katamanso\n* Krowor\n* Ledzokuku\n* Adentan\n* Ashiaman\n* La-Nkwantanang-Madina\n* La-Dade-Kotopon\n* Okaikwei North\n* Ablekuma North\n* Ablekuma West\n* Ablekuma Central\n* Ayawaso East\n* Ayawaso North\n* Ayawaso West\n* Ayawaso Central\n* Ga North\n* Ga West\n* Ga South\n* Ga Central\n* Ga East\n* Korle-Klottey\n* Awutu Senya East\n\n; affected districts in Ashanti Region:\n* Kumasi Metropolis\n* Asokwa\n* Suame\n* Old Tafo\n* Oforikrom\n* Asokore Mampong\n* Kwadaso\n* Atwima Nwabiagya\n* Kwabre East\n* Ejisu,Afigya-Kwabre South\n* Bosomtwe\n* Atwima Kwanwoma\n* Atwima Nwabiagya North\n*On '''31<sup>st</sup> March 2020''','''nine''' new cases were confirmed bringing the number to '''161'''. The new cases were all in Accra. Three of the infected persons had returned from journeys to Germany, France and Hungary. <ref name=\":0\" />\n*On 1 April 2020, the number of confirmed cases reached '''195''' with more security checkpoints and roadblocks set up in Accra. There was a bit of heavy vehicular traffic at many of the barriers and most commercial vehicles were not allowed to cross the Tema motorway.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.graphic.com.gh/news/general-news/lockdown-day-3-stranded-passengers-canes-traffic-no-mercy-for-trotros.html|title=#Lockdown Day 3: Stranded passengers, canes, traffic, no mercy for trotros|website=Graphic Online|language=en|access-date=2020-04-02}}</ref>\n*On 2 April 2020,'''nine''' new cases are confirmed, making the total '''204'''. All new cases are from the Greater Accra Region. The '''nine''' cases consist of '''four''' who have no contact with confirmed cases nor a travel history,'''four''' who are contacts of confirmed cases and one traveling to Ghana from Benin within the last '''14''' days.<ref name=\":0\" /> '''Two''' cases are in critical condition.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.graphic.com.gh/news/general-news/coronavirus-ghana-s-cases-hit-204-two-in-critical-condition.html|title=Coronavirus: Ghana's cases hit 204, two in critical condition|website=Graphic Online|language=en|access-date=2020-04-02}}</ref>\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist}}\n\n{{COVID-19}}\n\n[[Category:2019\u201320 coronavirus pandemic by country and territory|Ghana]]\n[[Category:2020 coronavirus pandemic in Africa|Ghana]]\n[[Category:2020 in Ghana|coronavirus pandemic]]\n[[Category:Medical outbreaks in Ghana]]\n", "name_user": "TereseB", "label": "safe", "comment": "corrected grammar", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/2020_coronavirus_pandemic_in_Ghana"}
{"title_page": "Something New (Wiz Khalifa song)", "text_new": "{{Infobox song\n| name       = Something New\n| cover      = WizKhalifaSomethingNew.jpg\n| alt        =\n| type       = single\n| artist     = [[Wiz Khalifa]] featuring [[Ty Dolla Sign]]\n| album      = [[Rolling Papers 2]]\n| released   = August 11, 2017;\nMarch 16, 2020 (Re-release)\n| format     = [[Music download|Digital download]]\n| recorded   = 2017\n| studio     =\n| venue      =\n| genre      =\n* [[Hip hop music|Hip hop]]\n* [[Contemporary R&B|R&B]]\n| length     = {{duration|m=3|s=20}}\n| label      = [[Atlantic Records|Atlantic]]\n| writer     = {{hlist|[[Wiz Khalifa|Cameron Thomaz]]|[[Ty Dolla Sign|Tyrone Griffin, Jr.]]|Dimitri McDowell}}\n| producer   = Ayo n Keyz & [[Hitmaka]]\n| chronology = [[Wiz Khalifa]]\n| prev_title = [[Gang Up]]\n| prev_year  = 2017\n| next_title = Type of Shit\n| next_year  = 2017\n| misc       = {{Extra chronology\n | artist     = [[Ty Dolla Sign]]\n | type       = single\n | prev_title = [[Love U Better]]\n | prev_year  = 2017\n | title      = Something New\n | year       = 2017\n | next_title = [[Ego (Ella Eyre song)|Ego]]\n | next_year  = 2017\n}}\n}}\n\"'''Something New'''\"  is a song by American rapper [[Wiz Khalifa]] featuring [[Taylor Gang Records|Taylor Gang]] label mate [[Ty Dolla Sign]] for his sixth studio album ''[[Rolling Papers 2]]'' (2018). It was released for [[Music download|digital download]] on August 11, 2017 by [[Atlantic Records]] as the album's [[lead single]]. The song was re-released on March 16, 2020 as the official lead single off Wiz Khalifa's upcoming 7th studio album. It was produced by Ayo n Keyz & [[Hitmaka]]. It heavily samples [[Zapp (band)|Zapp]]'s 1986 single \"[[Computer Love (Zapp song)|Computer Love]]\". The song received renewed popularity in 2020, thanks to its use in [[TikTok]] videos.\n\n==Background==\nWiz and Ty previewed the song and clips of the music video several times on [[Instagram]] throughout July 2017.<ref>https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=c4W7M6w3S88</ref><ref>https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=550j5yxgOzo</ref>\n\n==Composition==\n\"Something New\" is a \"feel-good love song\" featuring smooth, sultry vocals and a [[Rhythm#Composite rhythm|rhythmic]] chorus\u00a0from Ty Dolla $ign.<ref name=\"ComplexTikTok\">{{Cite web|url=https://www.complex.com/music/tiktok-songs-worth-listening-to/rod-wave-hear-on-ice|title=12 Songs Blowing Up on TikTok (That Are Actually Worth Listening to)|last=McKinney|first=Jessica|work=[[Complex (magazine)|Complex]]|date=March 26, 2020|accessdate=March 30, 2020}}</ref>\n\n==Commercial performance==\n\"Something New\" was the most added song to mainstream [[urban contemporary]] radio upon its release.<ref>{{citeweb|url=https://www.facebook.com/wizkhalifa/photos/a.133118481141.141020.12138756141/10155468647631142/?type=3&theater|title=Words can't explain how excited I am. Thank you for the support. Thank you @tydollasign @hitmaka @soundz and everyone else involved.|publisher=Facebook|accessdate=August 23, 2017}}</ref>\n\n==TikTok dance challenge==\n\nIn early 2020, the song began going viral on video-sharing app [[TikTok]], due to a dance challenge. The challenge sees participants line up behind each other, with one person in front to kick off the dance, and everyone else then proceeding to push each elbow out to the side before [[shimmy|shimmying]] along to the song's chorus and then clapping along to the beat.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.hotnewhiphop.com/ciara-and-russell-wilsons-family-take-on-viral-tiktok-challenge-news.106789.html?_amp|title=Ciara & Russell Wilson's Family Take On Viral TikTok Challenge|last=S.|first=Lynn|website=HotNewHipHop|date=March 19, 2020|accessdate=March 20, 2020}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=https://hollywoodlife.com/2020/03/19/jennifer-lopez-alex-rodriguez-family-tiktok-dance-challenge-something-new/|title=A-Rod & J.Lo Team Up With Their Kids For Epic TikTok Video & Fans Call It 'The Best' \u2014 Watch|website=[[HollywoodLife]]|last=Boren|first=Jade|date=March 19, 2020|accessdate=March 30, 2020}}</ref>\n\n== Music video ==\nOn August 14, 2017, Wiz uploaded the official music video for \"Something New\".<ref>https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=qxGapEwtq6g</ref> The plot involves various women robbing Wiz at his own house party behind his back. The video ends with all the women sneaking out and driving away while thanking him on [[Snapchat]] for allowing them to trick him. As of February 2020, the video has over 97 million views. Cameos include [[G-Eazy]], [[Lil Dicky]], [[Demi Lovato]], [[Jamie Foxx]], [[Juicy J]], [[Jason Derulo]], [[O.T. Genasis]], [[Todd Gurley]] and Bob Ross.\n\n==Charts==\n{| class=\"wikitable plainrowheaders sortable\" style=\"text-align:center;\"\n|-\n! scope=\"col\"| Chart (2017)\n! scope=\"col\"| Peak<br>position\n|-\n{{singlechart|Canada|94|artist=Wiz Khalifa|rowheader=true|accessdate=August 25, 2017}}\n|-\n{{singlechart|Hungarysingle|34|year=2017|week=33|artist=Wiz Khalifa|rowheader=true|accessdate=August 25, 2017}}\n|-\n{{singlechart|Billboardhot100|92|artist=Wiz Khalifa|rowheader=true|accessdate=August 23, 2017}}\n|-\n{{singlechart|Billboardrandbhiphop|37|artist=Wiz Khalifa|rowheader=true|accessdate=August 23, 2017}}\n|-\n{{singlechart|Billboardrhythmic|24|artist=Wiz Khalifa|rowheader=true|accessdate=October 17, 2017}}\n|}\n\n==Release history==\n{| class=\"wikitable\"\n|-\n!Country\n!Date\n!Format\n!Label\n|-\n|rowspan=\"2\"| United States\n|August 11, 2017\n| [[Music download|Digital download]]<ref name=\"iTunes\">{{cite web|url=https://itunes.apple.com/us/album/something-new-feat-ty-dolla-%24ign-single/id1267573353|title=Something New by Wiz Khalifa featuring Ty Dolla Sign |work=[[iTunes Store]] (US) |accessdate=August 23, 2017}}</ref>\n|rowspan=\"2\" | {{flatlist|\n* [[Taylor Gang Records|Taylor Gang]]\n* [[Atlantic Records|Atlantic]]\n}}\n|-\n| August&nbsp;22,&nbsp;2017\n| [[Urban contemporary|Urban]] radio<ref name=\"allaccess\">{{cite web|url=https://www.allaccess.com/urban/future-releases|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20170823091244/https://www.allaccess.com/urban/future-releases|archive-date=August 23, 2017|title=Urban/UAC Future Releases|publisher=All Access|accessdate=August 23, 2017}}</ref>\n|}\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist}}\n\n{{Wiz Khalifa singles}}\n{{Ty Dolla Sign}}\n\n[[Category:2017 songs]]\n[[Category:Wiz Khalifa songs]]\n[[Category:Songs written by Wiz Khalifa]]\n[[Category:2017 singles]]\n[[Category:Ty Dolla Sign songs]]\n[[Category:Atlantic Records singles]]\n[[Category:Songs written by Ty Dolla Sign]]\n[[Category:TikTok songs]]\n", "text_old": "{{Infobox song\n| name       = Something New\n| cover      = WizKhalifaSomethingNew.jpg\n| alt        =\n| type       = single\n| artist     = [[Wiz Khalifa]] featuring [[Ty Dolla Sign]]\n| album      = [[Rolling Papers 2]]\n| released   = August 11, 2017\n| format     = [[Music download|Digital download]]\n| recorded   = 2017\n| studio     =\n| venue      =\n| genre      =\n* [[Hip hop music|Hip hop]]\n* [[Contemporary R&B|R&B]]\n| length     = {{duration|m=3|s=20}}\n| label      = [[Atlantic Records|Atlantic]]\n| writer     = {{hlist|[[Wiz Khalifa|Cameron Thomaz]]|[[Ty Dolla Sign|Tyrone Griffin, Jr.]]|Dimitri McDowell}}\n| producer   = Ayo n Keyz & [[Hitmaka]]\n| chronology = [[Wiz Khalifa]]\n| prev_title = [[Gang Up]]\n| prev_year  = 2017\n| next_title = Type of Shit\n| next_year  = 2017\n| misc       = {{Extra chronology\n | artist     = [[Ty Dolla Sign]]\n | type       = single\n | prev_title = [[Love U Better]]\n | prev_year  = 2017\n | title      = Something New\n | year       = 2017\n | next_title = [[Ego (Ella Eyre song)|Ego]]\n | next_year  = 2017\n}}\n}}\n\"'''Something New'''\"  is a song by American rapper [[Wiz Khalifa]] featuring [[Taylor Gang Records|Taylor Gang]] label mate [[Ty Dolla Sign]] for his sixth studio album ''[[Rolling Papers 2]]'' (2018). It was released for [[Music download|digital download]] on August 11, 2017 by [[Atlantic Records]] as the album's [[lead single]]. The song was re-released on March 16, 2020 as the official lead single off Wiz Khalifa's upcoming 7th studio album. It was produced by Ayo n Keyz & [[Hitmaka]]. It heavily samples [[Zapp (band)|Zapp]]'s 1986 single \"[[Computer Love (Zapp song)|Computer Love]]\". The song received renewed popularity in 2020, thanks to its use in [[TikTok]] videos.\n\n==Background==\nWiz and Ty previewed the song and clips of the music video several times on [[Instagram]] throughout July 2017.<ref>https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=c4W7M6w3S88</ref><ref>https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=550j5yxgOzo</ref>\n\n==Composition==\n\"Something New\" is a \"feel-good love song\" featuring smooth, sultry vocals and a [[Rhythm#Composite rhythm|rhythmic]] chorus\u00a0from Ty Dolla $ign.<ref name=\"ComplexTikTok\">{{Cite web|url=https://www.complex.com/music/tiktok-songs-worth-listening-to/rod-wave-hear-on-ice|title=12 Songs Blowing Up on TikTok (That Are Actually Worth Listening to)|last=McKinney|first=Jessica|work=[[Complex (magazine)|Complex]]|date=March 26, 2020|accessdate=March 30, 2020}}</ref>\n\n==Commercial performance==\n\"Something New\" was the most added song to mainstream [[urban contemporary]] radio upon its release.<ref>{{citeweb|url=https://www.facebook.com/wizkhalifa/photos/a.133118481141.141020.12138756141/10155468647631142/?type=3&theater|title=Words can't explain how excited I am. Thank you for the support. Thank you @tydollasign @hitmaka @soundz and everyone else involved.|publisher=Facebook|accessdate=August 23, 2017}}</ref>\n\n==TikTok dance challenge==\n\nIn early 2020, the song began going viral on video-sharing app [[TikTok]], due to a dance challenge. The challenge sees participants line up behind each other, with one person in front to kick off the dance, and everyone else then proceeding to push each elbow out to the side before [[shimmy|shimmying]] along to the song's chorus and then clapping along to the beat.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.hotnewhiphop.com/ciara-and-russell-wilsons-family-take-on-viral-tiktok-challenge-news.106789.html?_amp|title=Ciara & Russell Wilson's Family Take On Viral TikTok Challenge|last=S.|first=Lynn|website=HotNewHipHop|date=March 19, 2020|accessdate=March 20, 2020}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=https://hollywoodlife.com/2020/03/19/jennifer-lopez-alex-rodriguez-family-tiktok-dance-challenge-something-new/|title=A-Rod & J.Lo Team Up With Their Kids For Epic TikTok Video & Fans Call It 'The Best' \u2014 Watch|website=[[HollywoodLife]]|last=Boren|first=Jade|date=March 19, 2020|accessdate=March 30, 2020}}</ref>\n\n== Music video ==\nOn August 14, 2017, Wiz uploaded the official music video for \"Something New\".<ref>https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=qxGapEwtq6g</ref> The plot involves various women robbing Wiz at his own house party behind his back. The video ends with all the women sneaking out and driving away while thanking him on [[Snapchat]] for allowing them to trick him. As of February 2020, the video has over 97 million views. Cameos include [[G-Eazy]], [[Lil Dicky]], [[Demi Lovato]], [[Jamie Foxx]], [[Juicy J]], [[Jason Derulo]], [[O.T. Genasis]], [[Todd Gurley]] and Bob Ross.\n\n==Charts==\n{| class=\"wikitable plainrowheaders sortable\" style=\"text-align:center;\"\n|-\n! scope=\"col\"| Chart (2017)\n! scope=\"col\"| Peak<br>position\n|-\n{{singlechart|Canada|94|artist=Wiz Khalifa|rowheader=true|accessdate=August 25, 2017}}\n|-\n{{singlechart|Hungarysingle|34|year=2017|week=33|artist=Wiz Khalifa|rowheader=true|accessdate=August 25, 2017}}\n|-\n{{singlechart|Billboardhot100|92|artist=Wiz Khalifa|rowheader=true|accessdate=August 23, 2017}}\n|-\n{{singlechart|Billboardrandbhiphop|37|artist=Wiz Khalifa|rowheader=true|accessdate=August 23, 2017}}\n|-\n{{singlechart|Billboardrhythmic|24|artist=Wiz Khalifa|rowheader=true|accessdate=October 17, 2017}}\n|}\n\n==Release history==\n{| class=\"wikitable\"\n|-\n!Country\n!Date\n!Format\n!Label\n|-\n|rowspan=\"2\"| United States\n|August 11, 2017\n| [[Music download|Digital download]]<ref name=\"iTunes\">{{cite web|url=https://itunes.apple.com/us/album/something-new-feat-ty-dolla-%24ign-single/id1267573353|title=Something New by Wiz Khalifa featuring Ty Dolla Sign |work=[[iTunes Store]] (US) |accessdate=August 23, 2017}}</ref>\n|rowspan=\"2\" | {{flatlist|\n* [[Taylor Gang Records|Taylor Gang]]\n* [[Atlantic Records|Atlantic]]\n}}\n|-\n| August&nbsp;22,&nbsp;2017\n| [[Urban contemporary|Urban]] radio<ref name=\"allaccess\">{{cite web|url=https://www.allaccess.com/urban/future-releases|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20170823091244/https://www.allaccess.com/urban/future-releases|archive-date=August 23, 2017|title=Urban/UAC Future Releases|publisher=All Access|accessdate=August 23, 2017}}</ref>\n|}\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist}}\n\n{{Wiz Khalifa singles}}\n{{Ty Dolla Sign}}\n\n[[Category:2017 songs]]\n[[Category:Wiz Khalifa songs]]\n[[Category:Songs written by Wiz Khalifa]]\n[[Category:2017 singles]]\n[[Category:Ty Dolla Sign songs]]\n[[Category:Atlantic Records singles]]\n[[Category:Songs written by Ty Dolla Sign]]\n[[Category:TikTok songs]]\n", "name_user": "Chase Burwasser", "label": "safe", "comment": "This is my idea.", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Something_New_(Wiz_Khalifa_song)"}
{"title_page": "1874\u201375 Scottish Cup", "text_new": "{{Use dmy dates|date=April 2012}}\n{{Infobox football tournament season\n|title              =1874\u201375 Scottish Cup\n|image              =[[File:Scottish cup.jpg|200px]]\n|imagesize          =\n|caption            =\n|country            =[[Scotland]]\n|num_teams          =25\n|defending champions=Queen's Park\n|champions          =Queen's Park<br /><small>(second title)</small>\n|runner-up          =Renton\n|matches            =27\n|goals              =56\n|top goal scorer    =\n|prevseason         =[[1873\u201374 Scottish Cup|1873\u201374]]\n|nextseason         =[[1875\u201376 Scottish Cup|1875\u201376]]\n}}\n\nThe '''1874\u201375 [[Scottish Cup]]''' \u2013 officially the '''Scottish Football Association Challenge Cup''' \u2013 was the second season of Scotland's most prestigious [[Association football|football]] knockout competition. Teams from [[Edinburgh]], [[Renfrewshire (historic)|Renfrewshire]] and [[Lanarkshire]] entered the competition for the first time and with 12 new teams entering the competition, a total of 25 were included in the first round draw.<ref name=\"Potter and Jones\">{{cite book |last1=Potter |first1=David |authorlink1=David W. Potter |last2=Jones |first2=Phil H. |date=2016 |title=The History of the Scottish Cup: The Story of Every Season 1873\u20132016 |location=Worthing |publisher=Pitch Publishing |page=14-15 |isbn=978-1-78531-214-4}}</ref> The competition began on 10 October 1874 and concluded with the final on 10 April 1875. The cup was won for the second time by [[Queen's Park F.C.|Queen's Park]] who defeated [[Dunbartonshire]] club [[Renton F.C.|Renton]] 3\u20130 in the final.<ref name=\"Final\">{{cite web |url=https://www.scottishfa.co.uk/scottish-cup-matches/?mid=91261 |title=Scottish Cup Matches |publisher=Scottish Football Association |accessdate=15 April 2019}}</ref>\n\n==Format==\n{{see also|Scottish Cup format}}\n\nAs with the inaugural competition, the second edition of the Scottish Cup took on the format of a traditional knockout tournament, however, an odd number of teams entering the competition necessitated the introduction of byes for the first time.<ref name=\"Potter and Jones\"/>\n\nFor the earlier rounds, the names of competing teams were placed into lots according to their districts and drawn into pairs. The home team for each tie was determined by the toss of a coin unless it was mutually agreed or only one of the two clubs drawn against one another had a private ground. In the event of a draw, the team who lost the toss would have the choice of ground for the replay. A similar procedure was used for subsequent rounds however, any club which had received a bye in the previous round would first be drawn against one of the winners of the previous round. The names of winning teams were placed into one lot for later rounds. The choice of venue for the final matches was reserved to the [[Scottish Football Association]].<ref>{{cite book |url=http://www.scottishsporthistory.com/uploads/3/3/6/0/3360867/scottish_football_annual_1875.pdf |title=Rules of the Scottish Football Association |publisher=Scottish Football Association |date=14 October 1875 |accessdate=9 October 2019}}</ref>\n\n===Calendar===\n\nThe exact dates of some matches are unknown as newspaper coverage of football in the late 19th century was not as comprehensive as it would become.<ref name=\"Potter and Jones\"/><ref name=\"Soccer Books\">{{cite book |date=2017 |title=Scottish F.A. Cup 1873\u20132017: The Complete Results |location=Cleethorpes |publisher=Soccer Books |page=3-4 |isbn=978-1-86223-366-9}}</ref>\n\n{|class=\"wikitable\" style=\"text-align: center\"\n!rowspan=2|Round\n!rowspan=2|First match date\n!colspan=3|Fixtures\n!rowspan=2 width=100|Clubs\n|-\n!width=55|Original\n!width=55|Byes\n!width=55|Replays\n|-\n|align=left|First round\n|align=left|October 1874\n|12\n|1\n|1\n|25 \u2192 13\n|-\n|align=left|Second round\n|align=left|November 1874\n|6\n|1\n|1\n|13 \u2192 7\n|-\n|align=left|Quarter-finals\n|align=left|19 December 1874\n|3\n|1\n|0\n|7 \u2192 4\n|-\n|align=left|Semi-finals\n|align=left|20 March 1875\n|2\n|0\n|3\n|4 \u2192 2\n|-\n|align=left|Final\n|align=left|10 April 1875\n|1\n|0\n|0\n|2 \u2192 1\n|}\n\n==Teams==\nAll 25 teams entered the competition in the first round.\n{| class=\"wikitable\" style=\"text-align:left\"\n|-\n![[Ayrshire]]\n![[Dunbartonshire]]\n![[Edinburgh]]\n!colspan=2|[[Glasgow]]\n![[Lanarkshire]]\n![[Renfrewshire (historic)|Renfrewshire]]\n|-\n|valign=top|\n*[[Kilmarnock F.C.|Kilmarnock]]\n|valign=top|\n*[[Dumbarton F.C.|Dumbarton]]\n*[[Helensburgh F.C.|Helensburgh]]\n*[[Renton F.C.|Renton]]\n*[[Star of Leven F.C.|Star of Leven]]\n*[[Vale of Leven F.C.|Vale of Leven]]\n*[[Vale of Leven Rovers F.C. (Alexandria)|Vale of Leven Rovers]]\n|valign=top|\n*[[St Bernard's F.C.|3rd Edinburgh RV]]\n|valign=top|\n*[[Alexandra Athletic F.C.|Alexandra Athletic]]\n*[[Blythswood F.C.|Blythswood]]\n*[[Clydesdale F.C.|Clydesdale]]\n*[[Dumbreck F.C.|Dumbreck]]\n*[[Eastern F.C.|Eastern]]\n*[[Oxford F.C.|Oxford]]\n*[[Queen's Park F.C.|Queen's Park]]\n|valign=top|\n*[[Standard F.C.|Standard]]\n*[[Rangers F.C.|Rangers]]\n*[[Rovers F.C.|Rovers]]\n*[[West End F.C. (Glasgow)|West End]]\n*[[Western F.C.|Western]]\n*[[Third Lanark A.C.|3rd Lanark RV]]\n*[[23rd Renfrewshire Rifle Volunteers F.C.|23rd Renfrew RV]]\n|valign=top|\n*[[Hamilton F.C. (1874\u201378)|Hamilton]]\n|valign=top|\n*[[Arthurlie F.C.|Arthurlie]]\n*[[Barrhead F.C.|Barrhead]]\n|}\n\n==First round==\nGlasgow team Standard were the first team in the competition's history to receive a bye and advanced straight to the second round.<ref name=\"Potter and Jones\"/><ref name=\"Soccer Books\"/> The first round got underway on 10 October 1874 when Rangers and Oxford made their Scottish Cup debuts. Goals from [[Moses McNeil|McNeil]] and Gibb gave Rangers a 2\u20130 home win at [[Glasgow Green#Flesher's Haugh|Flesher's Haugh]] to see them through.<ref name=\"Rangers v Oxford\">{{cite web |url=http://www.fitbastats.com/rangers/game.php?gameid=80449 |title=Rangers 2 - 0 Oxford, Scottish Cup (10/10/1874) |publisher=Fitbastats.com |accessdate=15 April 2019}}</ref> Dumbarton, Kilmarnock and Helensburgh - who were also making their debut in the competition - all recorded their first wins in the competition a week later. On the same day, Eastern secured their passage to the second with a 3\u20130 win over 23rd Renfrew RV and 3rd Lanark RV's tie with Barrhead went to a replay following a goalless draw at [[Cathkin Park (1872\u20131903)|Cathkin Park]].<ref name=\"Potter and Jones\"/><ref name=\"Soccer Books\"/><ref name=\"3LRV v Barrhead\">{{cite web |url=http://www.fitbastats.com/thirdlanark/game.php?gameid=80791 |title=Third Lanark 0 - 0 Barrhead Rangers, Scottish Cup (17/10/1874) |publisher=Fitbastats.com |accessdate=15 April 2019}}</ref> The remaining matches were played on 24 October 1874, however the exact date of West End's 3\u20130 win over Star of Leven is unknown. Holders Queen's Park defeated Western, Dumbreck won 5\u20131 against Alexandra Athletic, Clydesdale drew with Vale of Leven and 3rd Lanark RV defeated Barrhead in a replay.<ref name=\"Soccer Books\"/> Blythswood and Hamilton scratched their ties with Renton and Rovers respectively and Vale of Leven resigned before their replay with Clydesdale.<ref name=\"Soccer Books\"/><ref name=\"RSSSF\">{{cite web |url=http://www.rsssf.com/tabless/scotcuphistfull.html#1875 |title=Scotland - Cup Results 1873/74-1877/78 and 1889/90-1995/96 |publisher=The Rec.Sport.Soccer Statistics Foundation |accessdate=15 April 2019}}</ref>\n\n===Matches===\n{{Football box collapsible\n|date=10 October 1874\n|team1=Rangers\n|score=2\u20130\n|team2='''Oxford'''\n|goals1=\n*[[Moses McNeil|McNeil]] {{goal}}\n*Gibb {{goal}}\n|goals2=\n|stadium=[[Glasgow Green#Flesher's Haugh|Flesher's Haugh]]\n|location=[[Glasgow]]\n|attendance=\n|referee=\n|report=<ref name=\"Rangers v Oxford\"/>\n}}\n{{Football box collapsible\n|date=17 October 1874\n|team1=Dumbarton\n|score=3\u20130\n|team2='''Arthurlie'''\n|goals1=\n|goals2=\n|stadium=Boghead Park\n|location=[[Dumbarton]]\n|attendance=\n|referee=\n|report=<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.fitbastats.com/dumbarton/game.php?gameid=38137 |title=Dumbarton 3 - 0 Arthurlie, Scottish Cup (17/10/1874) |publisher=Fitbastats.com |accessdate=15 April 2019}}</ref><ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.sonsarchive.com/matchdetails.php?id=3 |title=Dumbarton 2-0 Arthurlie, Saturday, October 17th, 1874 |publisher=The Sons Archive |accessdate=16 April 2019}}</ref>\n}}\n{{Football box collapsible\n|date=17 October 1874\n|team1=Eastern\n|score=3\u20130\n|team2='''23rd Renfrew RV'''\n|goals1=\n|goals2=\n|stadium=\n|location=Glasgow\n|attendance=\n|referee=\n}}\n{{Football box collapsible\n|date=17 October 1874\n|team1=Helensburgh\n|score=3\u20130\n|team2='''3rd Edinburgh RV'''\n|goals1=\n|goals2=\n|stadium=\n|location=[[Helensburgh]]\n|attendance=\n|referee=\n}}\n{{Football box collapsible\n|date=17 October 1874\n|team1=Kilmarnock\n|score=4\u20130\n|team2='''Vale of Leven Rovers'''\n|goals1=\n*Sturrock {{goal}}\n*Brown {{goal}}\n*Wallace {{goal}}\n|goals2=\n|stadium=The Grange<ref name=\"Killie\">{{cite web |url=https://kilmarnockfc.co.uk/news/kilmarnock-in-history-birth-of-the-ayrshire-cup/ |title=Kilmarnock in History: Birth of the Ayrshire Cup |publisher=Kilmarnock FC |first=John |last=Livingston |date=24 March 2020 |accessdate=2 April 2020}}</ref>\n|location=[[Kilmarnock]]\n|attendance=\n|referee=\n|report=<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.fitbastats.com/kilmarnock/game.php?gameid=30932 |title=Kilmarnock 4 - 0 Vale of Leven Rovers, Scottish Cup (17/10/1874) |publisher=Fitbastats.com |accessdate=15 April 2019}}</ref>\n}}\n{{Football box collapsible\n|date=17 October 1874\n|team1='''3rd Lanark RV'''\n|score=0\u20130\n|team2='''Barrhead'''\n|goals1=\n|goals2=\n|stadium=[[Cathkin Park (1872\u20131903)|Cathkin Park]]\n|location=Glasgow\n|attendance=\n|referee=\n|report=<ref name=\"3LRV v Barrhead\"/>\n}}\n{{Football box collapsible\n|date=24 October 1874\n|team1='''Clydesdale'''\n|score=0\u20130\n|team2='''Vale of Leven'''\n|goals1=\n|goals2=\n|stadium=[[Kinning Park]]\n|location=Glasgow\n|attendance=\n|referee=\n|report=<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.fitbastats.com/valeofleven/game.php?gameid=88242 |title=Clydesdale Glasgow 0 - 0 Vale of Leven, Scottish Cup (24/10/1874) |publisher=Fitbastats.com |accessdate=15 April 2019}}</ref>\n}}\n{{Football box collapsible\n|date=24 October 1874\n|team1=Dumbreck\n|score=5\u20131\n|team2='''Alexandra Athletic'''\n|goals1=\n|goals2=\n|stadium=\n|location=Glasgow\n|attendance=\n|referee=\n}}\n{{Football box collapsible\n|date=24 October 1874\n|team1='''Western'''\n|score=0\u20131\n|team2=Queen's Park\n|goals1=\n|goals2=\n|stadium=Regent's Park\n|location=Glasgow\n|attendance=\n|referee=\n|report=<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.fitbastats.com/queenspark/game.php?gameid=75019 |title=Western 0 - 1 Queen's Park, Scottish Cup (24/10/1874) |publisher=Fitbastats.com |accessdate=12 April 2019}}</ref>\n}}\n{{Football box collapsible\n|date=Unknown{{Cref2|A}}\n|team1=West End\n|score=3\u20130\n|team2='''Star of Leven'''\n|goals1=\n|goals2=\n|stadium=\n|location=Glasgow\n|attendance=\n|referee=\n}}\n{{Football box collapsible\n|team1=Renton\n|score=[[walkover|w/o]]\n|team2='''Blythswood'''\n}}\n{{Football box collapsible\n|team1=Rovers\n|score=w/o\n|team2='''Hamilton'''\n}}\n\n====Replays====\n{{Football box collapsible\n|date=24 October 1874\n|team1=3rd Lanark RV\n|score=1\u20130\n|team2='''Barrhead'''\n|goals1=\n|goals2=\n|stadium=[[Cathkin Park (1872\u20131903)|Cathkin Park]]\n|location=Glasgow\n|attendance=\n|referee=\n|report=<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.fitbastats.com/thirdlanark/game.php?gameid=80792 |title=Third Lanark 1 - 0 Barrhead Rangers, Scottish Cup (24/10/1874) |publisher=Fitbastats.com |accessdate=15 April 2019}}</ref>\n}}\n{{Football box collapsible\n|team1=Clydesdale\n|score=w/o\n|team2='''Vale of Leven'''\n}}\n\n;Notes\n{{Cnote2 Begin|liststyle=disc}}\n{{Cnote2|A|'''A'''-The exact date of the West End vs. Star of Leven match is unknown, however it was played sometime between 10 and 24 October 1874.<ref name=\"Soccer Books\"/><ref name=\"London Hearts\">{{cite web |url=http://www.londonhearts.com/scores/sc/1874-75.html |title=Scottish Cup Results for 1874-75 |publisher=London Hearts Supporters Club |accessdate=15 April 2019}}</ref>}}\n{{Cnote2 End}}\n\n<small>Sources:<ref name=\"RSSSF\"/><ref name=\"London Hearts\"/><ref name=\"Scottish Football Archive\">{{cite web |url=http://scottishfootballarchive.co.uk/seasons/1874-75/scottishcup |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20091215121557/http://scottishfootballarchive.co.uk/seasons/1874-75/scottishcup |url-status=dead |archive-date=15 December 2009 |title=Scottish Cup 1874\u201375 |publisher=Scottish Football Archive |accessdate=8 September 2018}}</ref><ref name=\"Soccer Books\"/></small>\n\n==Second round==\nRovers received a bye to the quarter-finals. Queen's Park's 7\u20130 win over West End was the highest scoring game in the 1874\u201375 competition and equalled the record for the biggest win set by Queen's Park in the previous season.<ref name=\"QP v West End\">{{cite web |url=http://www.fitbastats.com/queenspark/game.php?gameid=75020 |title=Queen's Park 7 - 0 West End [sc], Scottish Cup (21/11/1874) |publisher=Fitbastats.com |accessdate=12 April 2019}}</ref>\n\n===Matches===\n{{Football box collapsible\n|date=21 November 1874\n|team1='''Kilmarnock'''\n|score=0\u20133\n|team2=Eastern\n|goals1=\n|goals2=\n|stadium=The Grange<ref name=\"Killie\"/>\n|location=Kilmarnock\n|attendance=\n|referee=\n|report=<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.fitbastats.com/kilmarnock/game.php?gameid=30933 |title=Eastern 3 - 0 Kilmarnock, Scottish Cup (21/11/1874) |publisher=Fitbastats.com |accessdate=15 April 2019}}</ref>\n}}\n{{Football box collapsible\n|date=21 November 1874\n|team1=Queen's Park\n|score=7\u20130\n|team2='''West End'''\n|goals1=\n|goals2=\n|stadium=[[Hampden Park (1873\u201383)|Hampden Park]]\n|location=Glasgow\n|attendance=\n|referee=\n|report=<ref name=\"QP v West End\"/>\n}}\n{{Football box collapsible\n|date=21 November 1874\n|team1='''Standard'''\n|score=0\u20130\n|team2='''3rd Lanark RV'''\n|goals1=\n|goals2=\n|stadium=Mossdale Park\n|location=Glasgow\n|attendance=\n|referee=\n|report=<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.fitbastats.com/thirdlanark/game.php?gameid=80793 |title=Standard 0 - 0 Third Lanark, Scottish Cup (21/11/1874) |publisher=Fitbastats.com |accessdate=15 April 2019}}</ref>\n}}\n{{Football box collapsible\n|date=28 November 1874\n|team1='''Rangers'''\n|score=0\u20130\n|team2='''Dumbarton'''\n|goals1=\n|goals2=\n|stadium=[[Glasgow Green#Flesher's Haugh|Flesher's Haugh]]\n|location=Glasgow\n|attendance=\n|referee=\n|report=<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.fitbastats.com/rangers/game.php?gameid=80450 |title=Rangers 0 - 0 Dumbarton, Scottish Cup (28/11/1874) |publisher=Fitbastats.com |accessdate=15 April 2019}}</ref><ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.fitbastats.com/dumbarton/game.php?gameid=80450 |title=Rangers 0 - 0 Dumbarton, Scottish Cup (28/11/1874) |publisher=Fitbastats.com |accessdate=15 April 2019}}</ref>\n}}\n{{Football box collapsible\n|date=Unknown\n|team1=Renton\n|score=2\u20130\n|team2='''Helensburgh'''\n|goals1=\n|goals2=\n|stadium=\n|location=[[Renton, West Dunbartonshire|Renton]]\n|attendance=\n|referee=\n}}\n{{Football box collapsible\n|date=Unknown\n|team1=Clydesdale\n|score=2\u20130\n|team2='''Dumbreck'''\n|goals1=\n|goals2=\n|stadium=\n|location=Glasgow\n|attendance=\n|referee=\n}}\n\n===Replays===\n{{Football box collapsible\n|date=28 November 1874\n|team1=3rd Lanark RV\n|score=2\u20130\n|team2='''Standard'''\n|goals1=\n|goals2=\n|stadium=[[Cathkin Park (1872\u20131903)|Cathkin Park]]\n|location=Glasgow\n|attendance=\n|referee=\n|report=<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.fitbastats.com/thirdlanark/game.php?gameid=80794 |title=Third Lanark 2 - 0 Standard, Scottish Cup (28/11/1874) |publisher=Fitbastats.com |accessdate=15 April 2019}}</ref>\n}}\n{{Football box collapsible\n|date=12 December 1874\n|team1=Dumbarton\n|score=1\u20130\n|team2='''Rangers'''\n|goals1=[[Archie Lang (footballer)|Lang]] {{goal}}\n|goals2=\n|stadium=Boghead Park\n|location=Dumbarton\n|attendance=\n|referee=\n|report=<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.fitbastats.com/rangers/game.php?gameid=80451 |title=Dumbarton 1 - 0 Rangers, Scottish Cup (12/12/1874) |publisher=Fitbastats.com |accessdate=15 April 2019}}</ref><ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.fitbastats.com/dumbarton/game.php?gameid=80451 |title=Dumbarton 1 - 0 Rangers, Scottish Cup (12/12/1874) |publisher=Fitbastats.com |accessdate=15 April 2019}}</ref><ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.sonsarchive.com/matchdetails.php?id=5 |title=Dumbarton 1-0 Rangers, Saturday, December 12th, 1874 |publisher=The Sons Archive |accessdate=15 April 2019}}</ref>\n}}\n\n<small>Sources:<ref name=\"RSSSF\"/><ref name=\"London Hearts\"/><ref name=\"Scottish Football Archive\"/><ref name=\"Soccer Books\"/></small>\n\n==Quarter-finals==\nClydesdale received a bye to the semi-finals.\n\n===Matches===\n{{Football box collapsible\n|date=19 December 1874\n|team1=Dumbarton\n|score=1\u20130\n|team2='''3rd Lanark RV'''\n|goals1=\n|goals2=\n|stadium=Boghead Park\n|location=Dumbarton\n|attendance=\n|referee=\n|report=<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.fitbastats.com/thirdlanark/game.php?gameid=38140 |title=Dumbarton 1 - 0 Third Lanark, Scottish Cup (26/12/1874) |publisher=Fitbastats.com |accessdate=15 April 2019}}</ref><ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.fitbastats.com/dumbarton/game.php?gameid=38140 |title=Dumbarton 1 - 0 Third Lanark, Scottish Cup (26/12/1874) |publisher=Fitbastats.com |accessdate=15 April 2019}}</ref><ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.sonsarchive.com/matchdetails.php?id=6 |title=Dumbarton 1-0 Third Lanark, Saturday, December 19th, 1874 |publisher=The Sons Archive |accessdate=15 April 2019}}</ref>\n}}\n{{Football box collapsible\n|date=26 December 1874\n|team1=Renton\n|score=1\u20130\n|team2='''Eastern'''\n|goals1=\n|goals2=\n|stadium=\n|location=Renton\n|attendance=\n|referee=\n}}\n{{Football box collapsible\n|team1=Queen's Park\n|score=w/o\n|team2='''Rovers'''\n}}\n\n<small>Sources:<ref name=\"RSSSF\"/><ref name=\"London Hearts\"/><ref name=\"Scottish Football Archive\"/><ref name=\"Soccer Books\"/></small>\n\n==Semi-finals==\n\n===Matches===\n{{Football box collapsible\n|date=20 March 1875\n|team1='''Clydesdale'''\n|score=0\u20130\n|team2='''Queen's Park'''\n|goals1=\n|goals2=\n|stadium=[[Kinning Park]]\n|location=Glasgow\n|attendance=\n|referee=\n|report=<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.fitbastats.com/queenspark/game.php?gameid=75021 |title=Clydesdale Glasgow 0 - 0 Queen's Park, Scottish Cup (20/03/1875) |publisher=Fitbastats.com |accessdate=12 April 2019}}</ref>\n}}\n{{Football box collapsible\n|date=27 March 1875\n|team1='''Renton'''\n|score=1\u20131\n|team2='''Dumbarton'''\n|goals1=\n|goals2=Galbraith {{goal}}\n|stadium=[[Tontine Park]]\n|location=Renton\n|attendance=\n|referee=\n|report=<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.fitbastats.com/dumbarton/game.php?gameid=38141 |title=Renton 1 - 1 Dumbarton, Scottish Cup (27/03/1875) |publisher=Fitbastats.com |accessdate=15 April 2019}}</ref><ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.sonsarchive.com/matchdetails.php?id=7 |title=Renton 1-1 Dumbarton, Saturday, March 27th, 1875 |publisher=The Sons Archive |accessdate=15 April 2019}}</ref>\n}}\n\n===Replays===\n{{Football box collapsible\n|date=27 March 1875\n|team1='''Queen's Park'''\n|score=2\u20132\n|team2='''Clydesdale'''\n|goals1=\n|goals2=\n|stadium=[[Hampden Park (1873\u201383)|Hampden Park]]\n|location=Glasgow\n|attendance=\n|referee=\n|report=<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.fitbastats.com/queenspark/game.php?gameid=75022 |title=Queen's Park 2 - 2 Clydesdale Glasgow, Scottish Cup (27/03/1875) |publisher=Fitbastats.com |accessdate=12 April 2019}}</ref>\n}}\n{{Football box collapsible\n|date=3 April 1875\n|team1='''Dumbarton'''\n|score=0\u20131\n|team2=Renton\n|goals1=\n|goals2=\n|stadium=Boghead Park\n|location=Dumbarton\n|attendance=\n|referee=\n|report=<ref>{{cite web |url=http://fitbastats.com/dumbarton/game.php?gameid=38142 |title=Renton 1 - 0 Dumbarton, Scottish Cup (03/04/1875) |publisher=Fitbastats.com |accessdate=15 April 2019}}</ref><ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.sonsarchive.com/matchdetails.php?id=8 |title=Dumbarton 1-0 Renton, Saturday, April 3rd, 1875 |publisher=The Sons Archive |accessdate=15 April 2019}}</ref>\n}}\n\n===Second Replay===\n{{Football box collapsible\n|date=3 April 1875\n|team1='''Clydesdale'''\n|score=0\u20131\n|team2=Queen's Park\n|goals1=\n|goals2=\n|stadium=[[Kinning Park]]\n|location=Glasgow\n|attendance=\n|referee=\n|report=<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.fitbastats.com/queenspark/game.php?gameid=75023 |title=Clydesdale Glasgow 0 - 1 Queen's Park, Scottish Cup (03/04/1875) |publisher=Fitbastats.com |accessdate=12 April 2019}}</ref>\n}}\n\n<small>Sources:<ref name=\"RSSSF\"/><ref name=\"London Hearts\"/><ref name=\"Scottish Football Archive\"/><ref name=\"Soccer Books\"/></small>\n\n==Final==\n{{main|1875 Scottish Cup Final}}\n{{Football box\n|date=10 April 1875\n|time=15:00\n|team1=Queen's Park\n|score=3\u20130\n|team2=Renton\n|goals1=*[[Angus MacKinnon|A. MacKinnon]] {{goal|55}}\n*[[Thomas Highet|Highet]] {{goal|70}}\n*[[Billy MacKinnon|B. MacKinnon]] {{goal|75}}\n|goals2=\n|stadium=[[Hampden Park (1873\u201383)|Hampden Park]]\n|location=Glasgow\n|attendance=7,000\n|referee=A. Campbell (Clydesdale)\n|report=<ref name=\"Potter and Jones\"/><ref name=\"Final\"/><ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.fitbastats.com/queenspark/game.php?gameid=75024 |title=Queen's Park 3 - 0 Renton, Scottish Cup (10/04/1875) |publisher=Fitbastats.com |accessdate=12 April 2019}}</ref>\n}}\n\n==See also==\n*[[1874\u201375 in Scottish football]]\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist}}\n\n{{Scottish Cup seasons}}\n{{1874\u201375 in Scottish football}}\n{{1874\u201375 in European football}}\n{{Portal bar|Association football|Scotland}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Scottish Cup 1874-75}}\n[[Category:Scottish Cup seasons|1874-75]]\n[[Category:1874\u201375 in Scottish football|Cup]]\n[[Category:1874\u201375 domestic association football cups]]\n", "text_old": "{{Use dmy dates|date=April 2012}}\n{{Infobox football tournament season\n|title              =1874\u201375 Scottish Cup\n|image              =[[File:Scottish cup.jpg|200px]]\n|imagesize          =\n|caption            =\n|country            =[[Scotland]]\n|num_teams          =25\n|defending champions=Queen's Park\n|champions          =Queen's Park<br /><small>(second title)</small>\n|runner-up          =Renton\n|matches            =27\n|goals              =56\n|top goal scorer    =\n|prevseason         =[[1873\u201374 Scottish Cup|1873\u201374]]\n|nextseason         =[[1875\u201376 Scottish Cup|1875\u201376]]\n}}\n\nThe '''1874\u201375 [[Scottish Cup]]''' \u2013 officially the '''Scottish Football Association Challenge Cup''' \u2013 was the second season of Scotland's most prestigious [[Association football|football]] knockout competition. Teams from [[Edinburgh]], [[Renfrewshire (historic)|Renfrewshire]] and [[Lanarkshire]] entered the competition for the first time and with 12 new teams entering the competition, a total of 25 were included in the first round draw.<ref name=\"Potter and Jones\">{{cite book |last1=Potter |first1=David |authorlink1=David W. Potter |last2=Jones |first2=Phil H. |date=2016 |title=The History of the Scottish Cup: The Story of Every Season 1873\u20132016 |location=Worthing |publisher=Pitch Publishing |page=14-15 |isbn=978-1-78531-214-4}}</ref> The competition began on 10 October 1874 and concluded with the final on 10 April 1875. The cup was won for the second time by [[Queen's Park F.C.|Queen's Park]] who defeated [[Dunbartonshire]] club [[Renton F.C.|Renton]] 3\u20130 in the final.<ref name=\"Final\">{{cite web |url=https://www.scottishfa.co.uk/scottish-cup-matches/?mid=91261 |title=Scottish Cup Matches |publisher=Scottish Football Association |accessdate=15 April 2019}}</ref>\n\n==Format==\n{{see also|Scottish Cup format}}\n\nAs with the inaugural competition, the second edition of the Scottish Cup took on the format of a traditional knockout tournament, however, an odd number of teams entering the competition necessitated the introduction of byes for the first time.<ref name=\"Potter and Jones\"/>\n\nFor the earlier rounds, the names of competing teams were placed into lots according to their districts and drawn into pairs. The home team for each tie was determined by the toss of a coin unless it was mutually agreed or only one of the two clubs drawn against one another had a private ground. In the event of a draw, the team who lost the toss would have the choice of ground for the replay. A similar procedure was used for subsequent rounds however, any club which had received a bye in the previous round would first be drawn against one of the winners of the previous round. The names of winning teams were placed into one lot for later rounds. The choice of venue for the final matches was reserved to the [[Scottish Football Association]].<ref>{{cite book |url=http://www.scottishsporthistory.com/uploads/3/3/6/0/3360867/scottish_football_annual_1875.pdf |title=Rules of the Scottish Football Association |publisher=Scottish Football Association |date=14 October 1875 |accessdate=9 October 2019}}</ref>\n\n===Calendar===\n\nThe exact dates of some matches are unknown as newspaper coverage of football in the late 19th century was not as comprehensive as it would become.<ref name=\"Potter and Jones\"/><ref name=\"Soccer Books\">{{cite book |date=2017 |title=Scottish F.A. Cup 1873\u20132017: The Complete Results |location=Cleethorpes |publisher=Soccer Books |page=3-4 |isbn=978-1-86223-366-9}}</ref>\n\n{|class=\"wikitable\" style=\"text-align: center\"\n!rowspan=2|Round\n!rowspan=2|First match date\n!colspan=3|Fixtures\n!rowspan=2 width=100|Clubs\n|-\n!width=55|Original\n!width=55|Byes\n!width=55|Replays\n|-\n|align=left|First round\n|align=left|October 1874\n|12\n|1\n|1\n|25 \u2192 13\n|-\n|align=left|Second round\n|align=left|November 1874\n|6\n|1\n|1\n|13 \u2192 7\n|-\n|align=left|Quarter-finals\n|align=left|19 December 1874\n|3\n|1\n|0\n|7 \u2192 4\n|-\n|align=left|Semi-finals\n|align=left|20 March 1875\n|2\n|0\n|3\n|4 \u2192 2\n|-\n|align=left|Final\n|align=left|10 April 1875\n|1\n|0\n|0\n|2 \u2192 1\n|}\n\n==Teams==\nAll 25 teams entered the competition in the first round.\n{| class=\"wikitable\" style=\"text-align:left\"\n|-\n![[Ayrshire]]\n![[Dunbartonshire]]\n![[Edinburgh]]\n!colspan=2|[[Glasgow]]\n![[Lanarkshire]]\n![[Renfrewshire (historic)|Renfrewshire]]\n|-\n|valign=top|\n*[[Kilmarnock F.C.|Kilmarnock]]\n|valign=top|\n*[[Dumbarton F.C.|Dumbarton]]\n*[[Helensburgh F.C.|Helensburgh]]\n*[[Renton F.C.|Renton]]\n*[[Star of Leven F.C.|Star of Leven]]\n*[[Vale of Leven F.C.|Vale of Leven]]\n*[[Vale of Leven Rovers F.C. (Alexandria)|Vale of Leven Rovers]]\n|valign=top|\n*[[St Bernard's F.C.|3rd Edinburgh RV]]\n|valign=top|\n*[[Alexandra Athletic F.C.|Alexandra Athletic]]\n*[[Blythswood F.C.|Blythswood]]\n*[[Clydesdale F.C.|Clydesdale]]\n*[[Dumbreck F.C.|Dumbreck]]\n*[[Eastern F.C.|Eastern]]\n*[[Oxford F.C.|Oxford]]\n*[[Queen's Park F.C.|Queen's Park]]\n|valign=top|\n*[[Standard F.C.|Standard]]\n*[[Rangers F.C.|Rangers]]\n*[[Rovers F.C.|Rovers]]\n*[[West End F.C. (Glasgow)|West End]]\n*[[Western F.C.|Western]]\n*[[Third Lanark A.C.|3rd Lanark RV]]\n*[[23rd Renfrewshire Rifle Volunteers F.C.|23rd Renfrew RV]]\n|valign=top|\n*[[Hamilton F.C. (1874\u201378)|Hamilton]]\n|valign=top|\n*[[Arthurlie F.C.|Arthurlie]]\n*[[Barrhead F.C.|Barrhead]]\n|}\n\n==First round==\nGlasgow team Standard were the first team in the competition's history to receive a bye and advanced straight to the second round.<ref name=\"Potter and Jones\"/><ref name=\"Soccer Books\"/> The first round got underway on 10 October 1874 when Rangers and Oxford made their Scottish Cup debuts. Goals from [[Moses McNeil|McNeil]] and Gibb gave Rangers a 2\u20130 home win at [[Glasgow Green#Flesher's Haugh|Flesher's Haugh]] to see them through.<ref name=\"Rangers v Oxford\">{{cite web |url=http://www.fitbastats.com/rangers/game.php?gameid=80449 |title=Rangers 2 - 0 Oxford, Scottish Cup (10/10/1874) |publisher=Fitbastats.com |accessdate=15 April 2019}}</ref> Dumbarton, Kilmarnock and Helensburgh - who were also making their debut in the competition - all recorded their first wins in the competition a week later. On the same day, Easter secured their passage to the second with a 3\u20130 win over 23rd Renfrew RV and 3rd Lanark RV's tie with Barrhead went to a replay following a goalless draw at [[Cathkin Park (1872\u20131903)|Cathkin Park]].<ref name=\"Potter and Jones\"/><ref name=\"Soccer Books\"/><ref name=\"3LRV v Barrhead\">{{cite web |url=http://www.fitbastats.com/thirdlanark/game.php?gameid=80791 |title=Third Lanark 0 - 0 Barrhead Rangers, Scottish Cup (17/10/1874) |publisher=Fitbastats.com |accessdate=15 April 2019}}</ref> The remaining matches were played on 24 October 1874, however the exact date of West End's 3\u20130 win over Star of Leven is unknown. Holders Queen's Park defeated Western, Dumbreck won 5\u20131 against Alexandra Athletic, Clydesdale drew with Vale of Leven and 3rd Lanark RV defeated Barrhead in a replay.<ref name=\"Soccer Books\"/> Blythswood and Hamilton scratched their ties with Renton and Rovers respectively and Vale of Leven resigned before their replay with Clydesdale.<ref name=\"Soccer Books\"/><ref name=\"RSSSF\">{{cite web |url=http://www.rsssf.com/tabless/scotcuphistfull.html#1875 |title=Scotland - Cup Results 1873/74-1877/78 and 1889/90-1995/96 |publisher=The Rec.Sport.Soccer Statistics Foundation |accessdate=15 April 2019}}</ref>\n\n===Matches===\n{{Football box collapsible\n|date=10 October 1874\n|team1=Rangers\n